  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The voluntary nature of open-source participation amplifies this effect, as contributors strategically select tasks where LLMs provide the greatest assistance over tasks where human \"question ingenuity\" still offers distinctive value (Shneiderman 2007).",
    "These findings provide robust empirical support for the hypothesis that developers are more likely to use LLMs for tasks where the surrounding context helps define both the problem and potential solutions.",
    "When a task has a \"right answer\" or well-defined success criteria, LLMs can effectively leverage their contextual understanding to generate appropriate responses (Doshi et al. 2024).",
    "The availability of welldefined success criteria also tends to result in solutions that are more familiar to other contributors in the community, increasing the acceptability of solutions.",
    "In contrast, tasks requiring higher-level abstraction without clear precedent may receive more modest benefits from current LLMs."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The voluntary nature of open-source participation amplifies this effect, as contributors strategically select tasks where LLMs provide the greatest assistance over tasks where human \"question ingenuity\" still offers distinctive value (Shneiderman 2007).",
